; Libertini suggests 2nd — 3rd century CE)",1,"low",[193,194],{"_":60,"type":61,"ref":62},{"_":64,"type":65,"ref":66},[196],[69,70],{"_":154,"role":76,"ref":155},{"_":199,"type":80},"KA0849",{"_":201,"mainLang":202,"languages":203},"Ancient Greek","grc",[201],{"n":86,"url":205,"height":88,"width":89,"desc":206,"surfaceType":91},"ISic002750_tiled.tif","I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana",[],[209,210,211,99],"Supplementum epigraphicum graecum, 1923-","Bulletin épigraphique, 1888-","Manganaro, 1994, Iscrizioni, epigrafi ed epigrammi in Greco della Sicilia orientale di epoca romana",[213,214,215,109],"F2GG87EQ","77P5MNIR","532NF7SV",[217,218,219,130,17,21,117,118,119,120,118,172,220,202],"isic002750","i.sicily inscription 002750",{"_":10},"ancient greek","Text encoding: Francesca Prado",{"file":223,"uri":223,"title":224,"status":225,"editionAuthor":11,"type":227,"objectType":231,"material":232,"condition":233,"layoutDesc":235,"handNote":240,"date":388,"places":392,"geo":395,"country":71,"region":72,"settlement":397,"repository":398,"idno":401,"textLang":403,"facsimile":405,"provenance":60,"letterHeights":408,"publications":409,"zotero":412,"keywords":415,"html":421},"ISic002945","A gymnasiarch crowns a group of youths",{"_":226},"edited",{"_":228,"ana":229,"ref":230},"honorific","#function.honorific","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/typeins/lod/69.html",{"_":17,"ana":18,"ref":19},{"_":21,"ana":22,"ref":23},{"ana":234},"#condition.fragment",{"layout":236},{"p":237,"rs":238,"damage":239},"15 neatly carved lines of Greek letters, of which the first four are larger. There appears to be a slight vacat at the top; lines 1-3 are indented by the equivalent of 1-2 characters at most; from line 4 onwards the left indentation increases, with clear vacats after lines 5 and 6, and a fixed left margin (c.7 cm vacat) from line 7 onwards; a vacat is consistently inserted between each name in the list from line 7 onwards.",{"_":30,"ana":31,"ref":32},{"ana":34},{"lettering":241,"dimensions":369},[242,243],"Elegant letters with minimal serifs/terminations visible on longer strokes (e.g. on tau, sigma and epsilon). Alpha has straight bar; beta has smaller upper loop, with the two loops connected without meeting the vertical; epsilon has shorter middle bar; theta is a full-size circle with a detached horizontal stroke at the centre; kappa has full length arms; mu has near vertical first and last strokes, with the middle strokes meeting a small way above the baseline; xsi is formed of vertical with three horizontals, the middle one of shorter length; omicron is full-size; pi has equal length vertical strokes; sigma has horizontal topo and bottom strokes; phi is ovoid, with vertical taller than other letters (14-15mm); omega full size, near circular, but open at the base. Traces of a secondary text include lunate epsilon (see commentary).",{"_":244,"ref":245},"\n                                    Types list:\n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                                    \n                       